Yup. Okay the tape is rolling so we're ready. So I'll reiterate, just how do you
go about editing a book? Okay well I'll tell you how I went about editing a

00:23.940 --> 00:35.980
book. I had the idea, this was way back in the early 70s, of doing a book of
science fiction by women, about women. I didn't think there'd be much point in

00:35.980 --> 00:47.320
doing science fiction by women and having it all be about men or something,
because, I mean, that wouldn't really focus the book, at least as far as I was

00:47.320 --> 00:59.540
concerned, it wouldn't. But I wanted to do something like that. It occurred to
me that there were a lot of stories that could be used, and then I tried to sell

00:59.540 --> 01:09.160
the book, and I couldn't sell it. I sent it around everywhere. I sent it from
the highest to the low. I mean, I sent it to schlocky publishers. I sent it to

01:09.160 --> 01:18.300
good publishers. I sent it to publishers in between the two extremes, and I
would get letters back saying, this is a very nice idea. Somebody should do

01:18.300 --> 01:27.860
this, but it isn't going to be us. Or this is very nice, but it has limited
appeal. You know, that was my favorite. I said, yes, it certainly does. It's

01:27.860 --> 01:33.800
only a little more than 50% of the population. But I

01:33.800 --> 01:35.540
was sending it around for about two years.

01:38.520 --> 01:49.420
And finally, when I was about ready to give up, I got a letter from Vonda
McIntyre who had found out that someone at Vintage Books was interested in an

01:49.420 --> 01:57.200
anthology of that kind. And in fact, I guess I asked her if she wanted to do
one. She had known that I was sending my book around and not having much luck

01:57.200 --> 02:09.520
with it. So she told me about this, which was, you know, too certainly kind of
for her to do. And I submitted the book to them and they took it. After that, I

02:09.520 --> 02:20.100
had to learn about editing because I had to start weeding things out. I had to
realize that I couldn't put every last thing in the book, that I had to have

02:20.100 --> 02:28.880
some sort of structure to the story, some sort of way of setting them up in the
book so that they sort of followed one from the other, I decided finally just to

02:28.880 --> 02:35.880
use the obvious method, which was to take the one that was published earliest
and put it at the beginning, and take the one that was published most recently

02:35.880 --> 02:44.040
and put it at the end so you sort of see how things progress over time. And then
after that I had to write the introduction, and that was probably the hardest

02:44.040 --> 02:53.960
part because I had to do quite a lot of research for that. But I think it helped
me, and I also think it probably aided the other two books, too, which I did

02:53.960 --> 03:05.200
later. The other two Women of Wonder books, I had not thought of doing them when
I did the first, and the publisher was the one that proposed them to me. They

03:05.200 --> 03:12.820
proposed the second one, first of all, and then asked me if I wanted to do a
third one also, thinking, I guess, that everything is supposed to come in threes

03:12.820 --> 03:17.600
nowadays. And that was why I did the other two.

03:21.220 --> 03:29.500
But I don't know if that would work for anyone else as far as if I were giving
advice to someone as to how to edit. But all I can say is if you have an idea

03:29.500 --> 03:38.860
that's really striking and you really feel that there's a lack of that
particular kind of book, that it is something that would be valuable to readers

03:38.860 --> 03:51.260
for many years, that presents certain stories that haven't been reprinted, or
that presents stories in a certain way that is self-informative. And if you're

03:51.260 --> 03:59.240
really determined, I think it's worth it just to keep sending the thing around
and sending it around and waiting until somebody buys it, at which point you

03:59.240 --> 04:05.960
will then learn about what editing a book is, I suppose. Since I didn't really
know what it was when I was sending the proposal around, I had to learn it as I

04:05.960 --> 04:16.300
was doing the first book. How do you get people to submit stories once the idea
is there? Well, what I did with this book is I had an easier task, I think,

04:16.380 --> 04:28.980
because I used stories that had already been published. But what I had to do is
I had to read about everything I could get my hands on, magazines, anthologies,

04:30.260 --> 04:47.380
old paperback reprints, everything, I had to read about probably 50 times as
many stories as I actually wound up publishing for each book. And then once I

04:47.380 --> 04:58.400
had the list of stories that I finally wanted to use, at that point I would
write to the authors. Of course, then you have the problem of what if somebody

04:58.400 --> 05:05.120
can't give you the rights to reprint the story then? And that happened to me a
couple of times. There were a couple of stories I wanted to use and I could not

05:05.120 --> 05:11.340
get permission for them. Not through any fault of the authors just because the
stories were tied up in some way.

05:14.460 --> 05:25.420
And that made it necessary to do a little restructuring on a couple of the
books. But overall, I'm satisfied with the way they turned out. and there wasn't

05:25.420 --> 05:35.760
a single story in any of them that I didn't like myself. I think that's
important. I think an editor has to pick stories that she likes for whatever

05:35.760 --> 05:41.380
reason and put those in rather than worrying about what someone else is going to
like.

05:44.700 --> 05:54.060
I think if you like the stories, someone else will too anyway. And the chances
are good if you try to get a variety of stories that you'll have something that

05:54.060 --> 05:55.340
appeals to almost anyone.

05:57.860 --> 06:07.800
So you aim for your taste, really, and if you want to be a commercial success,
you hope that your taste and those of the public at large jive. That's what I

06:07.800 --> 06:23.240
keep doing in everything. I suppose that's probably naive in some ways, but I
think I'd rather be naive than cynical. So I just don't think there's any point

06:23.240 --> 06:32.180
in worrying about what other people like. First of all, I think people like a
lot more things than many publishers are willing to admit or give them credit

06:32.180 --> 06:43.540
for liking. I mean, publishers talk as if there's a great appetite for junk, and
that's what they might as well publish. And yet whenever I talk to anybody, I

06:43.540 --> 06:53.500
hear things like, God, all this junk on the bookshelves, you know, or why are
they publishing all these trashy books or things like that? I hear that kind of

06:53.500 --> 06:59.840
comment all the time. Not just about science fiction. I mean, about a lot of
things. I don't think science fiction is the worst offender in this regard. It

06:59.840 --> 07:12.500
may be one of them, but it's not the worst. And I really don't think that there
is some appetite for junk. Everybody has, I suppose, their favorite little bit

07:12.500 --> 07:23.000
of junk that they like, or their particular vice. But I don't think the appetite
is as great as publishers think. I think a lot of publishers operate their

07:23.000 --> 07:32.880
companies as if they have contempt for the people who read the book. And I
especially think this is true, I'm afraid, among some of the science fiction

07:32.880 --> 07:45.200
editors. and it's too bad because i don't think the appetite for junk is quite
as large as they think and i do think that that good books that can can hang on

07:45.200 --> 07:56.140
and stay around for a while have a much better chance over the long run of doing
well for the publisher although the publishers don't seem to realize this i

07:56.140 --> 08:05.320
don't think you can concoct books in other words i think you can sit there and
try to concoct something that people are going to buy, I think you have to be

08:05.320 --> 08:12.340
sincere about it. Even if you write a lousy book, if you're sincere about
writing that lousy book, there are going to be a lot of readers who may respond

08:12.340 --> 08:22.600
to that sincerity. And however flawed the book may be, there'll be an essential
thing in it that readers will like or respond to in some way, even if it's not a

08:22.600 --> 08:33.560
critical success. But if you try to concoct something or deliberately set out to
engineer a book that's going to appeal to a lot of people, I just don't think it

08:33.560 --> 08:43.280
works. I think readers can spot that sort of thing. They may read it, they may
buy it if there's nothing else on the stand, but I don't think that they'll

08:43.280 --> 08:44.980
choose it if they have a choice.

